stylometry: @Risk allows the simulation to occur. @Risk takes information and does thousands of iterations for you so you dont have to take done all that information and average it out yourself. @Risk does this for you, it finds the averages, mean, median, standard deviation, min. & max .  When running a simulation with 5 inputs and 1000 iterations it gives the results of all those inputs.  It runs 1000 simulations for each input and then gives an average, median, standard deviation, min. & max. When analyzing the information I look at the standard deviation and try to fin the lowest one with the possibility of the least min. or out of the negatives for min amount of money made.
